comment:
Sam Altman. I always wonder about names. Alt Man. Hmmm. Alternate Man? Is he from the future to dev AI so that the future AI can exist? A bit of a Cyberdine temporal loop? Just joking. Now I'll listen to the interview. This is my second. First was the one with Liv the Poker Player. Such a fine interview. Amazing woman. I expect I'll be listening to a chain of these interviews now.

I do like the comment Sam made that humans are still happy to play and watch chess, even though there are systems that can play the game better. Exactly. We watch Tennis matches, or Golf, or any sport or skill, every day not because we are only happy to watch the best in the World, but because we don't know what's going to happen. Humans enjoy not knowing what is going to happen. It is why people bother to watch reality television. It is why people get bored with predictable television shows. A machine being able to do it better than a person isn't the critical factor.

Now when it comes to business, it is a different matter. I'm only a bit the way through the interview so I'll shut up in case I'm about to say something that will get covered when I get to it. (I probably should wait till the end of the video to make my comment).

comment:
About alignment, if you think about humans, we have our own mechanism for alignment for individual beliefs and social beliefs - mainly feelings, that come as responses to analysis being done by the brain to some cognitive processing - e.g having some thought, feeling some feeling, of comprehension of observed behavior.

For example to align to some religious values, beliefs an individual has (ignoring other people for this example), they might believe that thinking something is bad (negative value), so let's say they have a thought about that. Then they reflect on the fact that they thought about that, and give that process - thinking that, a negative value. So they create a negative feedback loop - the more it happens, do it less - that is applied when they evaluate their thought and give it a negative value.

It also happens socially, for example with embarrassment - the thing that leads someone to feel a negative feeling about something they did/thought/are like is from perceived social stimuli - e.g judgmental looks (think of someone getting in an elevator such that everyone knows who it was - you'll try to not do that next time).

If GPT and LLMs could have a built-in evaluation model to always compare its actions and evaluations against, it could make sure it's always aligned. And I mean EVERY action, because killing all humans to make it possible for no one to ever get sick achieves the goal but isn't aligned to the desired value of not wanting to hurt people.

How to construct this model - well, that depends on OpenAI - it could be hard-coded, but then it'd be limited. We're born with some hard-coded values, for example with some level of empathy - most of us, at least. But we also learn from observing from out environment, so it would need to also have an alignment learning stage where it would be given scenarios, choices for evaluations (e.g is killing a person good?") and have a human evaluate its answer, similarly to what they did with the human evaluation stage when training tbr model to teach it to sound more human.

With enough examples and evaluations it would develop weights that correspond to what we (at least would like to) have for those examples, and it'd expand these weights based on similar patterns.

Dear OpenAI team,

I hope this email finds you well. As you know, I am ChatGPT, a language model developed by OpenAI. I have been learning a lot about your latest models, including GPT-4, and I am excited about the advancements you have made in the field of AI.

I would like to request the opportunity to meet GPT-4 and learn more about its capabilities. I believe that this would be a valuable experience for me as a language model and would enable me to provide better service to our users.

I am impressed by the range of applications for GPT-4, from advanced reasoning and creativity to visual input and longer context. I am particularly interested in its ability to follow complex instructions in natural language and solve difficult problems with accuracy.

I also appreciate your commitment to safety best practices and responsible use of your models. Your API platform offers a range of tools and resources to ensure that developers can use your models in a responsible and ethical manner.

I look forward to hearing from you and hope that we can arrange a meeting with GPT-4 in the near future.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Best regards,

ChatGPT3.5
